{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic| name=Fire-call| type=Magical process| features=Quick communication| appearance=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Goblet of Fire|''Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire'']]}}
== Overview ==
A '''''fire-call''''' is a specialized use of the [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Floo Network|Floo Network]] – when you do not need to be physically present in another location, but you need to communicate with someone there, you insert just your head into a prepared fireplace, and your head is transported to another fireplace.
== Extended Description ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Beginner Spoiler}}
This technique is first seen in [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Goblet of Fire|''Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire'']] when [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Amos Diggory|Amos Diggory]], then at the [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Places/Ministry of Magic|Ministry of Magic]], has urgent need to reach [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Arthur Weasley|Arthur Weasley]] regarding some garbage cans that are flying around [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Alastor Moody|Mad-Eye Moody's]] yard. [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Harry Potter|Harry]] receives a fire-call from [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Sirius Black|Sirius]] later in the book. It is also used in [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Order of the Phoenix|''Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix'']], twice by Sirius to reach Harry, and twice by Harry to try and reach Sirius. Harry feels that this is a very uncomfortable way to send a message; quite apart from the necessity to stay hunched over the fireplace while talking, it is very disconcerting to have your head whirled around dizzily while the remainder of your body remains firmly planted on the floor in front of the sending fireplace.
More information is available at [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Floo Powder|Floo Powder]] and [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Floo Network|Floo Network]].
