=Numbers and Time=
==Numbers== The Greek words from 1 to 10 are presented along with English words derived from them: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | ένα | unary |- | δύο | duet |- | τρία | trio |- | τέσσερα | tesseract |- | πεντε | pentagon |- | έξι | hexagon |- | επτά | heptathlon |- | οκτώ | octopus |- | εννέα | ennead |- | δέκα | decathlon |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=2e}}
The Greek word for ''one'' also serves as the indefinite article and changes case like this:
{| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | ένας | ''one,'' masculine subject |- | έναν | ''one,'' masculine object |- |- | μία or μια | ''one,'' feminine subject |- | μία or μια | ''one,'' feminine object |- |- | ένα | ''one,'' neuter subject |- | ένα | ''one,'' neuter object |- |}
(The genitive forms are covered in lesson 3.)
Example: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | Ενας σκύλος δαγκώνει έναν άνθρωπο. | A dog bites a man. |- |} ==Time== {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | Η ώρα είναι οκτώ. | The time is eight o'clock. |- | Είναι οκτώ. | It's eight o'clock. |- | Είναι οκτώ και δέκα. | It's ten past eight. |}
Because ώρα is feminine, the feminine forms of the numbers are used for time: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | Είναι τέσσερις. | It's four o'clock. |- |}
Vocabulary: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | παρά (short of) | in expressions of time, "to" |- | και (and) | in expressions of time, "past" |- | ακριβώς (exactly) | in expressions of time, "sharp" |- | μισή | half (feminine form, used with the feminine ώρα) |- | τέταρτο | quarter |}
Examples: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | Είναι οκτώ παρά δέκα. | It's ten to eight. |- | Είναι οκτώ ακριβώς. | It's eight o'clock sharp. |- | Είναι οκτώ και μισή. | It's half past eight. |- | Είναι οκτώ και τέταρτο. | It's quarter past eight. |} ===Vocabulary relating to time=== {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | το πρωί | the morning |- | το μεσημέρι | the noon |- | το απόγευμα | the afternoon |- | το βράδυ | the evening |- | η νύχτα | the night |- | το ρολόι | the clock (~Spanish "reloj") |- | νωρίς | early |- | αργά | late |}
====Usage of noon, afternoon etc.====
Be careful, the words may have the same literal meaning, but they do not correspond to the same time! Morning is between 5am to 12pm. Noon for Greeks is approximately between 12pm to 4pm. The afternoon is approximately between 4 to 8pm. The evening is from 8pm to 12am and the night comes afterwards. However in actual speech "night" is rarely used when specifying the time. Usually both "evening" and "morning" are used for times between 1am and 2am. Afterwards it is always "morning". Although, if asked, people will refer to the time between 3am and 5am as "night", when specifying the time they will refer to it as "morning".
{| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | Γιατί με ξυπνάς στις τρεις το πρωί; | Why are you waking me up at three o'clock in the morning? |- | Μείναμε στο εστιατόριο μέχρι τις δύο to βράδυ. | We stayed at the restaurant until two o'clock in the evening. |}
[[Category:Modern Greek]]

=The days of the week= Several of the days of the week have names related to numbers. Except for Σαββατο, Saturday, which is neuter, they are all feminine. {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | Κυριακή (Lord's day) | Sunday |- | Δευτέρα (Second day) | Monday |- | Τρίτη (Third day) | Tuesday |- | Τετάρτη (Fourth day) | Wednesday |- | Πέμπτη (Fifth day) | Thursday |- | Παρασκευή ("Preparation") | Friday |- | Σάββατο ("Sabbath") | Saturday |}
Vocabulary: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | η μέρα | the day |- | χτες (alt.sp. χθες) | yesterday |- | σήμερα | today |- | αύριο | tomorrow |}
==Saying what day it is==
This is the way I would assume that it would be said. Is capitalising standard? Is the form of my question right? Is it idiomatic?
{| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" |Είναι Παρασκευή. |It is Friday. |- |Σήμερα είναι τετάρτη. |Today is wednesday. |- |Τι η μέρα είναι? |What day is it? |}
[[Category:Modern Greek]]

=Sentences= The order of words in a Greek sentence is much more free than in English, but you can correctly construct a sentence using the familiar English syntax of subject+verb, or subject+verb+object. The subject is usually omitted when it is a pronoun.
Sentences: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | Είναι καλό. | It is good. |- | Είναι κακό. | It is bad. |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1l}}
In Greek, adjectives change their endings to agree with the gender and number of the nouns they describe (''declension''). The following vocabulary list introduces some nouns that happen to be neuter, and some adjectives, which are given in neuter form. The word το is the definite article, like English "the," used with singular neuter nouns.
Vocabulary: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | νερό | water |- | κρασί | wine |- | τσάι | tea |- | καυτό | hot |- | κρύο | cold |- | άσπρο | white |- | κόκκινο | red |- | θέλω | to want |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1m}}
Sentences: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | Το νερό είναι κρύο. | The water is cold |- | Το κρασί είναι κρύο. | The wine is cold. |- | Το τσάι είναι καυτό. | The tea is hot. |- | Το άσπρο κρασί είναι κρύο. | The white wine is cold. |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1n}}
Negatives are formed by placing ''δεν'' before the verb. The question mark in Greek is the semicolon.
Sentences: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | Το κόκκινο κρασί δεν είναι κρύο. | The red wine is not cold |- | Το νερό δεν είναι καυτό. | The water is not hot. |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1o}}
Dialog: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | Χαίρετε. | Hello. |- | Χαίρετε. | Hello. |- | Έχετε τσάι; | Do you have tea? |- | Οχι, δεν έχουμε τσάι. Θέλετε νερό; | No, we don't have tea. Do you want water? |- | Ναι, ευχαριστώ. | Yes, thank you. |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1p}}
=Money/To χρήμα, τα λεφτά=
Greece uses the euro, το ευρώ, as its currency. One hundredth of a euro is ενα λεπτό. Both words are neuter, and the plural and singular forms of ευρώ are the same.
{| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" |το ευρώ |τα ευρώ |- |το λεπτό |τα λεπτά |}
Dialog in a wine shop: {| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | Τι θέλετε; | What would you like? |- | Πόσο κάνει το μπουκάλι; | How much is the bottle? |- | Εννέα ευρώ και δεκα λεπτά. | Nine euros and ten cents. |}
[[Category:Modern Greek]]

