== Verbs == === First Conjugation ===
{| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | γράφω | γράφουμε |- | γράφεις | γράφετε |- | γράφει | γράφουν |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1i}}
====The verbs έχω, ''to have,'' and είμαι, ''to be''==== Two important verbs are έχω, ''to have,'' and είμαι, ''to be.'' The first-conjugation verb έχω is regular in the present tense, so it has the same endings as γράφω.
{| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | έχω | έχουμε |- | έχεις | έχετε |- | έχει | έχουν |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1j}}
''To be'' in English is expressed in the active voice, but the Greek είμαι is passive, and doesn't have an active form. The ending -μαι is a typical, regular ending for passive verbs.
{| align="center" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" | είμαι | είμαστε |- | είσαι | είστε |- | είναι | είναι |- |} {{Modern_Greek/audio_nonnative|which=1k}}
==Pronouns==
Pronouns have cases, number and gender just as regular nouns do. To make the tables appear simpler, the pronouns have been separated into persons.
{| align="center" border="yes" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" |First Person |- | | Singular | | Plural |- |Nominative |εγώ |I |εμείς |we |- |Genitive | μου | mine | μας | ours |- |Accusative | με | me | μας | us |- |}
{| align="center" border="yes" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" |Second Person |- | | Singular | | Plural |- |Nominative | εσύ | you | εσείς | you |- |- |Genitive | σου | yours | σας | yours |- |Accusative | σε | you | σας | you |}
{| align="center" border="yes" style="background:#{{Modern Greek/table_audio_color}}" |Third |Person |- | | | Singular | | | | Plural | |- | Gender | M | F | N | | M | F | N | |- |N | αυτός | αυτή | αυτό | he, she, it | αυτοί | αυτές | αυτά | they |- |- |G | του | της | του | his, her, its | τους | τους | τους | their |- |A | τον | την | το | him, her, it | τους | τους | τα | they |}
===Links === [http://web.archive.org/20020530051112/www.geocities.com/alexandrosworld/Greek/Pronouns.html| A page with more on pronouns]
[[Category:Modern Greek]]

The model here is to set up a client like app, and at regular intervals, call the server code's handler on a once through (no loop) mode. Note the odd way this is crafted so that the poll function is called '''after''' the orb's process loop times-out. So, what can happen here is that the handler can call out to other ORBs and the run() member of the local orb can act as a part time server. According to the TAO Developer's manual, the TCP stack will act as your cache while the poll function is doing its thing, thus, don't spend too much time in the poll function.

<pre>
  MyHandler ph;

  //Set up a delay value of 6 s
  ACE_Time_Value interval (6, 0);
  //Run the ORB's event loop and poll the bill acceptor
  while(1){
    orb->run(interval);
    ph.poll();
  }
  orb->destroy ();
</pre>

