{{C sharp/Navigation|Keywords|out}}

The {{C sharp|out}} keyword explicitly specifies that a variable should be passed ''by reference'' to a method, and set in that method. A variable using this keyword must ''not'' be intialized before the method call to ensure the developer understand its intended effects. Using this keyword requires the called method to set the variable using this modifier before returning. Using {{C sharp/kw|out|{{C sharp|out}}}} also requires the developer to specify the keyword even in the calling code, to ensure that it is easily visible to developers reading the code that the variable will have its value changed elsewhere, which is useful when analyzing the program flow.

An example of passing a variable with {{C sharp/kw|out|{{C sharp|out}}}} follows:

<code>
 {{C sharp/kw|void}} CallingMethod()
 {
    {{C sharp/kw|int}} i;
    SetDependingOnTime({{C sharp/kw|out}} i);
    // i is now 10 before/at 12 am, or 20 after
 }

 {{C sharp/kw|void}} SetDependingOnTime({{C sharp/kw|out}} {{C sharp/kw|int}} iValue)
 {
   iValue = DateTime.Now.Hour <= 12 ? 10 : 20;
 }
</code>

{{C sharp/Keywords}}

[[Category:C Sharp Programming Keywords|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

{{C sharp/Navigation|Keywords|sizeof}}

The {{C sharp|sizeof}} keyword returns how many bytes an object requires to be stored.

An example usage:
<code>
 {{C sharp/kw|int}} i = 123456;

 Console.WriteLine("Storing i, a {0}, requires {1} bytes, or {2} bits.",
   i.GetType(), {{C sharp/kw|sizeof}}(i), {{C sharp/kw|sizeof}}(i)*8);

 // outputs "Storing i, a System.Int32, requires 4 bytes, or 32 bits."
</code>

